##College Entrance Examination countdown to 100 days, this year's senior students can only "cloud oath division. "

Wechat, bingdianweekly

Features, China Youth Daily's in depth reporting brand. We believe that news has more than one day of life.

A high school senior holds a table filled with books at the Shelter Hospital of Hongshan Gymnasium in Wuhan on Feb. 21. China Youth Daily, China Youth Daily reporter Lu Chong / photo

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Author | Zhongqingbao Zhongqingwang journalist, Cheng Mengchao

Editor | Chen Zhuo

No matter how special 2020 is, something will happen. Like the SATS.

According to the usual schedule, the 2020 college entrance examination will enter the 100-day countdown on February 28. For High School Seniors in the shadow of the epidemic, that is another challenge they must pull out all the stops.

They haven't been able to return to class yet. In Yantai, Shandong Province, all high school seniors in a county are required to take a picture of their desks and send it to their teachers at 6:30 a.m. and 10 p.m. Even so, one of the school's Chinese teachers was not reassured. He would start calling his students at 6:30 every morning to ask them to recite the classical Chinese.

More than one high school senior said that the "countdown to the college entrance examination" on the blackboard in the classroom had been moved to the class's QQ group. Many of them now rely on the software to prepare for exams online.

This unusual test preparation method leaves a boy in Wuhan feeling like he wants to be a pilot, but the online class on his mobile phone hurts his eyes. He should do eye exercises at every break.

For another wuhan-based candidate, he must first soothe his own anxiety. During the Spring Festival, he got up every day, first look at two mobile phones: Today and many more cases, the college entrance examination countdown another day less.

At that time, with a mobile phone to see online classes, do the topic of his total can not help but switch screen, a glance at the overwhelming news. He said he was nervous about the outbreak because it was his life at the moment, and because he was anxious about the Gaokao, which is his future.

He needs to choose. By February, he had uninstalled the news APP and stopped reading too much. He must return to his studies.

"unique" senior year

The special period study prepares for an examination, always meets the unexpected challenge, the network question is only one of them.

Su Xiaoying, a senior at a High School in Liangshan Yi Autonomous Prefecture, Sichuan Province, said that her class was scheduled to review live with a well known high school in Chengdu, and that everyone was looking forward to it. But after the test, many students found that the speed of the net simply is not good.

More worrying for her is that some of the students in her class who are doing well have never checked in recently. "I'm afraid they don't have Internet. "

Many of her teachers are in the countryside, and the network environment is worse than the students. Daily Q & A, some teachers reply slowly, students simply in the class group to discuss with each other, to solve their own.

Chen Xingcai is the senior third grade director of a county in Kunming. He told the China Youth Daily, China Youth Daily and China Youth Daily that even for video classes with low Internet requirements, more than 100 of the roughly 1,200 students in the entire grade could not attend on time because of poor Internet access or lack of contact.

There's a lot of chatter about internet speeds. A senior in high school in Chengdu said she was afraid of the Internet in her math class -- as if she couldn't keep up with a question for half a minute. A few times, one lesson passed in confusion and anxiety.

Li Kai teaches senior history at a high school on the outskirts of Chengdu. Of the more than 90 students in the two classes, about 20 are from the surrounding mountains. These kids have been buying cell-phone packets for live-streaming classes. Several students said that they could not hear clearly for more than ten minutes in a class. His heart ached.

"A good teacher has to interact with others, and use the Internet, but try to overcome it. " When Li Kai used to grade test papers, he would ask, "why did you choose the wrong question? " Nowadays, many students do not have voice-based question-and-answer support on the Internet, dozens of people type on the chat bar -- Foshan is slow and inarticulate.

He found that there is no interaction network teaching, can only put all knowledge point "flood irrigation. ". People around me exclaim: You talk too fast in class now.

Lee was in a hurry. Teachers are required to come to school every day and broadcast live from the podium. Looking at the empty seats, he wanted to laugh and cry: Every class time is very tight, but the efficiency is low, is "no way. ".

A student summary: Top students feel "network class" inefficient, poor students simply do not listen to this form of the most suitable for middle-class students.

One of Li's students told him that although someone had signed up for self-study early in the class, they were still lying in bed. Zhu, a senior class teacher at a high school in Zhangye, Gansu Province, checks the backstage of a live-streaming class every day and finds that some students drop out after only 15 minutes of a class. He takes roll call in class, and about 30% of the students are always absent. After the fact, the reason is similar, "I went to the toilet. " More students consensus is: Listen to the net class, a little attention will be distracted.

Both teachers and parents stress self-control. The problem is, it didn't happen overnight. A high school senior in Hunan admits to spending hours a day reviewing on short videos, games and social media with his mobile phone. A senior student complained that he could not settle down at home and watched a play all day. And at night, regret and anxiety and crying. When I got up the next day, I didn't want to study any more.

Most students know they have to be nervous in their senior year. But at home the inevitable efficiency is limited, the day passes, then doubly frustrated. They tend to ask around with their friends. Do you study more at home?

If our school's acceptance rate is gonNA drop

He told reporters that Kunming's education bureau had organised "master classes" for the city's senior three students, which were broadcast live and recorded.

Chen Xingcai also knows that this is the best solution at present for schools in remote areas with insufficient hardware. But the problem is that the course is aimed at students all over the city. Some of his students find it difficult and always ask him on their mobile phones, can Not keep up with how to do, the class of a top girl, has "teacher class" do not understand the knowledge points tidied up to the notebook, dense, said to go back to school after teachers to solve.

In Xinhuang Dong Autonomous County, Hunan Province, a student surnamed Tao, who was preparing to take a calligraphy test, said his school had no choice but to let them watch the video with other classes.

"I don't understand a word in math class, " he said.

"This year, our school admission rate will decline? " Worry Chen Xingcai. In his view, when the role of the secondary school, the urban conditions of good families, can give more help to children. Chu Chaohui, a researcher at the Institute of Education Sciences, agreed: "students in schools, especially those in rural areas, have been affected by the outbreak. "

When students who are sitting in a classroom are separated in different places, a lot of things can pull them apart. Sometimes having a printer in the house can be a hindrance. A Sichuan girl has only one mobile phone, exercises in the mobile phone, the teacher's live video of the problem, she had to switch back and forth between the two, "switch on the blindfold. "

An extra computer or mobile phone can solve some problems, but many rural and even county homes do not have these devices. In any case, answering a question on a blank sheet of paper and submitting it to a photograph is one that many schools explicitly require to be the closest to the Gaokao situation.

There are questions: In addition to the examination papers, textbooks, review materials in the side? During the holidays, many people put them together at school.

In the home preparation time, the sports students are probably the loudest. On the short video platform, many of them have recently become Internet celebrities: Alternatives to weight-lifting barbells include but are not limited to vats of mineral water, wooden stakes and hollow concrete blocks. In one video, a sportsperson in a rural area of Henan province lifts a rusty tricycle wheel hub at home for strength training. Others run across empty country concrete roads with hemp rope tied around their waists and tugging on oversized tires. Others practice jumping jacks at home, and eventually messages come from downstairs: What's going on in your house?

Zhu, the teacher in Gansu Province, has been getting calls from the students in her class saying she doesn't know how to prepare for the exam.

"Do you want to practice on the vacant lot first? "

After a while, the phone rings again. "teacher, we don't even let people off the building. "

He has a headache.

Peng Xinye, a student from Wuhan, will take the art exam this year, but he has been confined to a bed for most of the year. He was diagnosed with new crown pneumonia and was among the first patients admitted to the shelter hospital in the early hours of February 6.

Came in a hurry, no lamp, no paper, no pencil. The hospital gave each patient a small box, which he used as a stool, lying on his stomach in bed for Internet lessons. Gym Class was arranged, and he was doing crunches in bed. The doctors and nurses gave him a lot of blank paper for his homework. The lights in the shelter went out at 11 every night, and the outermost circle of lights fell dimly on the bed. The nurses and security guards on duty always asked him if he wanted to go to the on-call room, where the light was good.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Sketches made by Peng Xinye in the shelter hospital

Changing and unchanging

Many students feel anxious about the college entrance examination, but there are always some who are more anxious than others. Art candidates are part of it. Most of the national art candidates will temporarily put aside their cultural courses after the end of the second year of high school, Start Professional Training, and take part in the provincial professional examinations and the examinations of professional colleges and universities in other provinces one after another; if there are no accidents, all professional examinations will be over in february-march 2020, and then spend the last 100-odd days storming classes.

But now, something unexpected has happened.

The mother of a wuhan-based art candidate rushed her child through all the institutions she could find that had not yet closed its doors.

But in the meantime, she must comfort the child. She has found her children in a state of anxiety lately, and has begun to deliberately share "positive" News, like, "there are many more provinces to help us today. ". The wechat group, a tutoring group for children, has also set a rule that anyone who sends "bad" messages will be kicked out of the group.

The calligraphy test taker, surnamed Tao in Hunan, was due to complete his final professional exam on Feb. 23. He said he was now "more confused than anxious" : would he have to take every test, even if the exams resumed in March? Do you have to attend pre-exam training classes around your college? For Art candidates, this is a common way to improve their academic performance. But then again, what about the cultural studies exam in June?

Others face more uncertainty. A mother and daughter from Suzhou are stranded in a neighborhood near Wuhan Conservatory of Music. On January 17, Ms. Li arranged for her daughter to come here for training.

Three days later, my daughter said, there were a lot of voices dragging suitcases around the neighborhood. Everyone's evacuating. She wants to go home. Ms. Lee has to insist. On January 22nd, she came, too, after her business with the company. Wuhan was sealed off a day later.

For some time afterward, the mother felt her daughter's zither sound become sad. She felt sorry for her daughter. "She was always asked to listen to me. But this time, I was wrong. "

This out-of-town art examination trainees live together in a rented community, the recent announcement of the playing less. In addition to those who left, many students who were also stranded began to review their studies. For Ms. Li's daughters, if classes in Suzhou were to resume in early March, they would be separated for 14 days after leaving Wuhan, too late. One way to combat the uncertainty is to spend money -- as if she were hiring a private tutor, one on one, for more than $30,000 a month.

But in any case of anxiety, test preparation must be carried out. A video recently circulated on the Internet shows a high school senior who has no Wi-Fi signal in his home climbing onto his roof every morning to receive his neighbor's Internet for an online class. Rooftop boy says his target is a Zhejiang University.

In Wangcang, Sichuan Province, a girl walks up and down a mountain road for an hour every day, sitting on the edge of a cliff to study. The Village Council had the only Wi-Fi signal in the village, but it was closed during the outbreak. I can get a signal up there from the cliffs.

A netizen from Henan Province posted on Weibo that two high school seniors in their hometown village had built a shelter outside the walls of a small courtyard to surf the Internet. The Primary School Wall is the wheat field, only in the wall has a circle of earth bag can stay. The students brought over wooden tables, bamboo stools, and a brazier.

A good student in Dongguan, Guangdong Province, told the China Youth Daily website that for her, online review is more efficient than traditional classes. In her class, only math classes are guaranteed four hours a week of live webcasts, while Chinese and other subjects are interspersed with case studies, assignments, and videos. The school gives advice on subjects for each session of the day, but it is not mandatory. Teachers have plenty of time to respond to questions as soon as they are sent. She was able to fill in the gaps and make up for the weaknesses.

Teachers are adjusting their teaching plans, Chen said. After the beginning of the school year, we must make every effort to seize the time to catch up with the progress of review.

The girl in his class, who had asked for exercises and materials from friends at a well-known high school in Kunming, found that she was much more flexible in solving problems, no matter what they were. It's a bonus.

A girl has her own agenda. Before the Spring Festival in school, sometimes can not finish the homework, she fell asleep at 1:00 every night. When School Starts, she sleeps later, no matter what time it is, "make sure you get the job done. "

In Wuhan, teacher in charge of the class recently always call Peng Xinye, ask him how today's body, how about the shelter, review there is no fall.

Peng Xinye in school is the kind of mischievous students, teachers arranged in the first row of the classroom. He said he wasn't used to being taken care of lately.

His review didn't go well. After all, there's a lot of noise in the shelter. It's easy to get distracted in online class. A few days ago, he had a CT scan and an infection in his lung; he also tested positive for nucleic acid and is still in the hospital.

But without looking at those indicators, his body was almost completely healed, "able to eat, drink, jump, and sleep. " In late January, his parents had a fever, and by the time they were admitted, both had recovered on their own and the nucleic acid had turned negative.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"Cut, they two get me in, oneself pour first good. " Peng Xinye now casually mention this matter, like a daily complaint.

After a tour of the ward, he realized that he might be the only college student in the ward. His friends would come by to cheer him up; the nurses would check up on him from time to time; sometimes he would brush his cell phone at night and go to bed late, and the nurses would come to him and say, "go to sleep, are you going to study tomorrow? "

One day, he finished drawing a picture, then fell asleep, the picture is at hand. When he awoke, people gathered around him, holding up his paintings and studying them. An aunt said, his daughter just the year before last art exam, can give him a lot of experience, must exchange. The conversation soon picked up. It's a new day.

He sent his painting of "a life in a shelter" to twitter -- as nurses bent over two patients in bed. On the wall of the hospital in the painting, he wrote four words on purpose: "refueling in Wuhan. "
